sentences: Alice Carter Simmons (March 1883  – March 30, 1943) was an American pianist, organist, and music educator.

She was the founding secretary of the National Association of Negro Musicians (NANM), and was head of the instrumental music program at Tuskegee Institute beginning in 1916; she also taught at Fisk University.

Simmons completed teacher training at Tuskegee Institute in 1903, graduated from Fisk University in 1908, and pursued further training as a pianist at the Oberlin Conservatory of Music in 1908 and 1909, completing a Bachelor of Music degree in 1930.

In 1910, Simmons played the first-night concert to open the Morton Theatre in Athens, Georgia.
From 1910 to 1911, she was on the faculty of the Elizabeth City State Teachers College in North Carolina.
In 1916, she became head of the division of instrumental music at Tuskegee Institute.
She was founding secretary of the National Association of Negro Musicians, when it organized in 1919.
In 1931, she helped organize a choir competition at Fisk University.
She became secretary-treasurer of NANM in 1922, remained on the board through the mid-1920s, and was active at the organization's national conventions into the 1930s.
